A wide variety of glycosylated compounds exhibit(cid:2) ing  antibiotic  activity  and  isolated  from  different sources, including microorganisms, plants, and some animals,  has  been  studied  [1,  2].  Sugar  residues  of most antibiotics belong to the family of 6(cid:2)deoxyhex(cid:2) oses.  In  recent  years,  an  increasing  number  of  genes involved in their biosynthesis were cloned and charac(cid:2) terized in the genomes of various actinomycetes [2, 3]. The presence of these sugar residues determines anti(cid:2) tumor effects of most antibiotics, plays an important role in the recognition of cell targets, and influences the pharmacokinetics of these compounds [4]. There(cid:2) fore, investigation of the biosynthesis of the glycoside moiety  of  the  antibiotics  and  development  of approaches  to  engineering  antibiotic  producers  with modified  sugar  residues  and  new  aglycone(cid:2)binding sites are of theoretical and practical importance.

Streptomyces  nogalater  Lv65  is  a  producer  of  an anticancer  antibiotic  nogalamycin  (Fig.  1)  [5].  Its derivatives are used in chemotherapy of tumors. Cer(cid:2) tain aspects of the regulation of nogalamycin produc(cid:2) tion  have  been  characterized  [6–8].  However,  most enzymatic reactions of nogalamycin biosynthesis have not been studied. The mechanisms controlling forma(cid:2) tion  of  the  sugar  moieties  of  nogalamycin  and  their enzymatic modification, particularly methylation, are not known [9, 10]. Investigation  of  O(cid:2)methyltransferase  genes  modi(cid:2) fying the sugar moieties of nogalamycin will contrib(cid:2) 1 Corresponding author; e(cid:2)mail: v_fedorenko@franko.lviv.ua Abstract—Nogalamycin is a polyketide antibiotic produced by Streptomyces nogalater Lv65. Antibiotic is gly(cid:2) cosylated  with  nogalose  and  nogalamine  sugar  moieties.  Bioinformatic  analysis  of  the snogM,  snogL, and snogY genes revealed that the products of these genes were involved in methylation of the nogalose moiety of nogalamycin.  Disruption  of  the  snogM,  snogL,  and  snogY  genes  in  the  chromosome  of  S.  nogalater  Lv65 resulted in S. nogalater strains ΔsnogM, ΔsnogL, and ΔsnogY. Inactivation of the O(cid:2)methyltransferase genes had  no  affect  on  the  antibiotic  activity  and  morphological  features  of  the  recombinant  strains.  Genetic manipulations with the snogM, snogL, and snogY genes of the nogalamycin biosynthetic gene cluster are a potentially valuable tool for generation of novel anthracycline antibiotics.

Detailed characterization of O(cid:2)methyltrans(cid:2) ferase genes, as well as of their products, is a prerequi(cid:2) site  for  synthesis  of  new  anthracyclines.  Therefore, directed mutagenesis of O(cid:2)methyltransferase genes is of high priority. The goal of the work was insertional inactivation of the snogM, snogL, and snogY genes and bioinformatic analysis of their translation products. In the other branch, protein separation into two groups was observed, one containing SnogM and methyltransferases of  S. lavendulae NRRL 2564 (paralogues MitM and MitN) and Streptomyces paten(cid:2) sis  subsp.  rosaceus  NRRL  18993.  A  separate  branch was formed by methyltransferase of S. graminofaciens A(cid:2)8890.  Analysis  of  the  probable  amino  acid sequences of SnogY and its homologues (Fig. 4) indi(cid:2) cated the formation of distinct branches of paralogues, in  particular,  for  methyltransferases  of  S.  echinatus (Orf19 and Orf24) and S. steffibyrgensis NRRL 3193 (StfMII  and  StfMIII).  The  proteins  of  S.  echinatus and  S.  steffisburgensis  NRRL  3193  were  the  most homologous to SnogY. The  results  of  phylogenetic  analysis  indicated  the high homology rate between proteins SnogM, SnogL, and SnogY with O(cid:2)methyltransferases involved in bio(cid:2) synthesis of various antibiotics. Multiple comparisons of methyltransferases from the gene clusters of antibi(cid:2) otic  biosynthesis  also  evidenced  the  formation  of  a conservative group of proteins having a common pre(cid:2) cursor.

For  disruption  of  the  snogM,  snogL,  and  snogY genes they were substituted with mutant alleles in the chromosome  of  S.  nogalater  Lv65.  For  this  purpose, plasmids  pKM::aadA,  pKL::aadA,  and  pKY::aadA were  transferred  into  S.  nogalater  cells  using  E.  coli ET12567 (pUB307). The average rate of transconju(cid:2) gant  formation  was  (4.7  ±  0.2)  ×  10–7.  To  obtain S. nogalater  strains  with  inactivated  O(cid:2)methyltrans(cid:2) ferase  genes,  we  selected  the  transconjugant  strains and cultivated them on TSB medium for five days at 39°C. This temperature is non(cid:2)permissive for replica(cid:2) tion of the created plasmids that contain a heat(cid:2)sensi(cid:2) tive replicon of pSG5 plasmid [13]. Phenotype verifi(cid:2) cation of transconjugant strains thus obtained made it possible  to  separate  them  into  two  classes:  spectino(cid:2) mycin(cid:2)  and  apramycin(cid:2)resistant  ones  (ApmR  SpcR), which appeared as a result of a single crossing(cid:2)over and spectinomycin(cid:2)resistant  apramycin(cid:2)sensitive  (ApmS SpcR), which were formed in a double crossing(cid:2)over. The  fact  of  gene  disruption  was  confirmed  by DNA–DNA hybridization. We used the EcoRI/Hin(cid:2) dIII  fragments  of  pKM102,  pKL102,  and  pKY102 plasmids (2.1, 2.4, and 1.6 kb long respectively). The labeled  2.1(cid:2)kb  probe  was  hybridized  with  a  4.7(cid:2)kb EcoRV fragment of S. nogalater Lv65 total DNA and a 6.7(cid:2)kb EcoRV fragment of S. nogalater ΔsnogM total DNA. Apparently, the 6.7(cid:2)kb fragment was formed as a result of integration of the 2.0(cid:2)kb aadА gene into the unique SmaI site of the snogM gene. The results con(cid:2) firm  the  fact  of  the  snogM  gene  inactivation  in  the chromosome  of  S.  nogalater  Lv65  (Fig.  5a).  Similar experiments were carried out to confirm disruption of the snogL and snogY genes. The labeled 2.4(cid:2)kb probe was  hybridized  with  a  6.1(cid:2)kb  PstI  fragment  of S. nogalater  Lv65  total  DNA  and  a  8.1(cid:2)kb  PstI  frag(cid:2) ment of S. nogalater ΔsnogL total DNA (Fig. 5b). The labeled 1.6(cid:2)kb probe of pKY102 plasmid was hybrid(cid:2) ized with a 3.8(cid:2)kb EcoRI fragment of S. nogalater Lv65 total  DNA  and  a  5.8(cid:2)kb  EcoRI  fragment  of S. nogalater  ΔsnogY  total  DNA  (Fig.  5c). Knockout of the snogM, snogL, and snogY genes did not  affect  the  morphological  characteristics  of  the bacteria  (for  example,  size  and  shape  of  colonies, spore  formation)  grown  on  OM,  SM,  and  Bennett complex media, as well as on the Hopwood and Cza(cid:2) pek minimal media. We studied the effect of nogalamycin methyltrans(cid:2) ferases  inactivation  on  the  antibiotic  activity  of S. nogalater strains. Average values of productivity of recombinant  strains  and  S.  nogalater  Lv65  wild(cid:2)type strain  were  2.3  ±  0.1.  These  results  indicated  that directed inactivation of O(cid:2)methyltransferase genes did not affect antibiotic activity of S. nogalater and were in agreement  with  the  previously  obtained  literature  data for a number of antibiotics [2]. However, the new com(cid:2) pounds may be of interest for clinical application since modification of the sugar residues of anthracycline anti(cid:2) biotics determines their antitumor properties. Therefore, the data of bioinformatic analysis allow us  to  assume  that  the  products  of  the  snogM,  snogL, and  snogY  genes  are  involved  in  methylation  of  the nogalose  residues  during  nogalamycin  biosynthesis. Directed  inactivation  of  these  genes  in  the  chromo(cid:2) some of S. nogalater Lv65 does not affect the antibiotic activity  and  morphological  characteristics  of  the S. nogalater. However, our experiments demonstrated METHYLATION  OF  NOGALOSE  DURING  NOGALOMYCIN  BIOSYNTHESIS

the  possibility  to  produce  new  nogalamycins  by knockout  inactivation  of  the  O(cid:2)methyltransferase genes  involved  in  modification  of  the  nogalamycin sugar moiety. Detailed structural analysis of new com(cid:2) pounds produced by the recombinant strains will make it possible to elucidate their chemical properties and spectrum  of  biological  activities.  The  information obtained is of importance for research on the mecha(cid:2) nisms of genetic regulation of nogalamycin biosynthe(cid:2) sis; the obtained strains might be used in experiments on  anthracycline  O(cid:2)methyltransferase  heterologous gene expression. Establishment of phylogenetic rela(cid:2) tions in this family of proteins is a valuable instrument for investigation of their evolutionary patterns.
